<script>\
const Q=[\
  // Systems Design\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"easy",q:"What does SDLC stand for?",opts:["Software Design Life Cycle","Systems Development Life Cycle","Systems Deployment and Launch Cycle","Software Development and Launch Cycle"],a:1,exp:"SDLC stands for Systems Development Life Cycle \'97 the structured process for planning, creating, testing, and deploying an information system."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"easy",q:"Which SDLC phase involves defining what the new system must do?",opts:["Design","Implementation","Systems Analysis","Maintenance"],a:2,exp:"Systems Analysis is where requirements are gathered and the current system is studied to define what the new system needs to accomplish."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"easy",q:"Financial feasibility examines:",opts:["Technical skills of the team","Whether the budget justifies the project","How users adapt to the system","Network infrastructure requirements"],a:1,exp:"Financial feasibility determines whether the project is affordable and whether the expected benefits justify the cost."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"easy",q:"Validation in systems development asks:",opts:["Was the system built correctly?","Were all bugs removed?","Does the system meet user needs?","Is the code syntax correct?"],a:2,exp:"Validation ensures the right system was built \'97 it checks whether the product satisfies actual business requirements."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"easy",q:"A Data Flow Diagram (DFD) primarily shows:",opts:["Database table relationships","How data moves through a system","Class hierarchies","Project timelines"],a:1,exp:"DFDs illustrate how data flows between processes, data stores, and external entities within a system."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"easy",q:"Which SDLC phase comes immediately after Design?",opts:["Analysis","Planning","Implementation","Maintenance"],a:2,exp:"After Design, Implementation involves building, coding, and installing the system."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"easy",q:"Organizational feasibility examines whether:",opts:["The technology exists to build the system","The budget is sufficient","The organization can adapt to the new system","The system meets legal requirements"],a:2,exp:"Organizational feasibility evaluates whether the company's culture, structure, and staff can successfully adopt the new system."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"medium",q:"Which is NOT a typical SDLC phase?",opts:["Planning","Marketing","Analysis","Maintenance"],a:1,exp:"Marketing is not a phase of the SDLC. Typical phases are Planning, Analysis, Design, Implementation, and Maintenance."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"medium",q:"Verification in systems development asks:",opts:["Does the system meet user needs?","Was the system built correctly?","Is the system financially viable?","Are stakeholders satisfied?"],a:1,exp:"Verification confirms the system was built correctly \'97 it checks that the product matches its design specifications."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"medium",q:"Which artifact shows relationships between database entities using keys?",opts:["Data Flow Diagram","Class Diagram","Entity Relationship Diagram","Gantt Chart"],a:2,exp:"An ERD maps entities (tables), their attributes, and the relationships between them using primary and foreign keys."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"medium",q:"Technical feasibility evaluates:",opts:["Whether the budget is sufficient","Whether the org has the technical expertise and hardware","Whether users will accept the new system","Whether the timeline is realistic"],a:1,exp:"Technical feasibility evaluates whether the organization has the hardware, software, and skill required to build and maintain the system."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"medium",q:"Which requirements-gathering method lets users interact with a working model to clarify needs?",opts:["Surveys","Interviews","Direct Observation","Prototyping"],a:3,exp:"Prototyping lets users interact with a working model of the system to refine requirements they couldn't easily articulate verbally."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"medium",q:"A class diagram is associated with which development approach?",opts:["Waterfall only","Procedural programming","Object-oriented design","Network infrastructure planning"],a:2,exp:"Class diagrams are part of UML and are used in object-oriented system design to show classes, attributes, methods, and relationships."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"hard",q:"In a DFD, an external entity is represented by a:",opts:["Circle","Rectangle","Arrow","Open-ended rectangle"],a:1,exp:"External entities (people or systems outside the boundary) are shown as rectangles in a DFD. Circles represent processes."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"hard",q:"Which conversion method runs old and new systems simultaneously?",opts:["Direct cutover","Parallel conversion","Pilot conversion","Phased conversion"],a:1,exp:"Parallel conversion runs both systems at once, comparing outputs. It's safest but most expensive since both must be maintained."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"hard",q:"Which UML diagram captures end-user interactions with the system?",opts:["Class Diagram","Entity Relationship Diagram","Use Case Diagram","Data Flow Diagram"],a:2,exp:"Use Case Diagrams show how actors (end users) interact with a system's functions, ideal for capturing behavioral requirements."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"hard",q:"A context diagram (Level 0 DFD) shows:",opts:["Internal process details","The system as a single process with all external entities","All database tables and keys","Class inheritance hierarchies"],a:1,exp:"A context diagram represents the entire system as one process, showing external entities and major data flows at the highest level of abstraction."\},\
  \{t:"Systems Design",d:"hard",q:"Which SDLC model best handles rapidly changing requirements?",opts:["Waterfall","Critical Path","Agile","Feasibility Study"],a:2,exp:"Agile is iterative and flexible, designed to accommodate changing requirements through short development cycles and continuous feedback."\},\
  // OOP\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"easy",q:"What is an object in OOP?",opts:["A function","An instance of a class","A variable name","A database table"],a:1,exp:"An object is a specific instance of a class. It contains real data and can use the methods defined by its class."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"easy",q:"Which OOP concept bundles data and methods and hides internal details?",opts:["Inheritance","Polymorphism","Encapsulation","Abstraction"],a:2,exp:"Encapsulation wraps data and methods into a single unit (class) and restricts direct access to internal data."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"easy",q:"A `Dog` class that acquires all properties of an `Animal` class demonstrates:",opts:["Polymorphism","Encapsulation","Abstraction","Inheritance"],a:3,exp:"Inheritance allows a subclass (Dog) to inherit attributes and methods from a parent class (Animal)."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"easy",q:"Which of these is NOT a core OOP principle?",opts:["Encapsulation","Recursion","Polymorphism","Inheritance"],a:1,exp:"The four core OOP principles are Encapsulation, Abstraction, Polymorphism, and Inheritance. Recursion is a technique, not an OOP principle."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"easy",q:"What does an attribute represent in a class?",opts:["A behavior the object can perform","A value stored by the object","A relationship between classes","A reusable code library"],a:1,exp:"Attributes (fields or properties) store the data and state associated with an object."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"easy",q:"What is a constructor?",opts:["A method that destroys objects","A special method called when a new object is created","A list of all class attributes","A method inherited from a parent class"],a:1,exp:"A constructor is a special method automatically called when a new object is instantiated, initializing its attributes."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"medium",q:"A `Shape` class has a `draw()` method. `Circle` and `Square` both override it differently. This is:",opts:["Encapsulation","Abstraction","Inheritance","Polymorphism"],a:3,exp:"Polymorphism allows subclasses to provide their own implementation of a method defined in a parent class."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"medium",q:"Which OOP principle hides complex implementation and shows only essential features?",opts:["Encapsulation","Polymorphism","Abstraction","Inheritance"],a:2,exp:"Abstraction simplifies complex systems by exposing only what is necessary and hiding internal complexity."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"medium",q:"A method with the same name but different parameter types uses:",opts:["Overriding","Overloading","Inheritance","Abstraction"],a:1,exp:"Method overloading allows multiple methods with the same name but different parameters to coexist in the same class."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"medium",q:"Which of the following is NOT a modern OOP language?",opts:["Python","Java","C++","SQL"],a:3,exp:"SQL is a query language for databases, not an OOP language. Python, Java, and C++ are all OOP languages."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"medium",q:"What is a framework in OOP?",opts:["A single reusable function","A collection of pre-written classes and tools providing structure for building apps","A debugging tool","A type of database query"],a:1,exp:"A framework provides a foundation of pre-written code, patterns, and tools that developers build upon rather than starting from scratch."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"hard",q:"An abstract class differs from an interface in that:",opts:["Abstract classes can have implemented methods; interfaces traditionally cannot","Interfaces support inheritance; abstract classes do not","Abstract classes can only have one method","Interfaces cannot be extended"],a:0,exp:"Abstract classes can contain both implemented and abstract methods. Interfaces traditionally define only method signatures without implementation."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"hard",q:"Which best illustrates inheritance in a business system?",opts:["A form validates email format","A Manager class reuses all Employee attributes without rewriting them","A query returns sorted results","A firewall blocks access"],a:1,exp:"Inheritance eliminates code duplication. A Manager inherits all Employee attributes (name, salary, ID) and adds manager-specific ones."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"hard",q:"Low coupling in OOP means:",opts:["Classes have many methods","Classes are highly dependent on each other","Classes have minimal dependencies on each other","All classes share the same parent"],a:2,exp:"Low coupling means classes are minimally dependent on each other, making the system easier to maintain, test, and modify independently."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"hard",q:"The Single Responsibility Principle states:",opts:["A class should be open for extension but closed for modification","A class should have only one reason to change","Subclasses should be substitutable for parent classes","Interfaces should be specific, not general"],a:1,exp:"SRP from SOLID design states each class should have only one job or reason to change, making code easier to maintain."\},\
  \{t:"OOP",d:"hard",q:"Method overriding is when:",opts:["Two methods share a name with different parameters","A subclass provides its own implementation of a parent class method","A private method is hidden from subclasses","A method is called from another library"],a:1,exp:"Overriding allows a subclass to replace the parent class's method with its own specific implementation."\},\
  // Data\
  \{t:"Data",d:"easy",q:"Which SQL keyword retrieves data from a table?",opts:["INSERT","UPDATE","SELECT","DELETE"],a:2,exp:"SELECT is used to query and retrieve data from one or more database tables."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"easy",q:"What is a primary key?",opts:["A key used to encrypt data","A unique identifier for each record in a table","A column that links two tables","The first column in every table"],a:1,exp:"A primary key uniquely identifies each row in a table. No two rows can share the same value, and it cannot be NULL."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"easy",q:"What does a foreign key do?",opts:["Encrypts sensitive columns","Links a record in one table to a record in another","Speeds up queries","Prevents duplicate rows"],a:1,exp:"A foreign key creates a relationship between two tables by referencing the primary key of another table."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"easy",q:"In a relational database, a row is also called a:",opts:["Field","Schema","Tuple","Key"],a:2,exp:"A tuple is another term for a row or record in a relational database table."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"easy",q:"What does NoSQL stand for?",opts:["Not Only SQL","No Standard Query Language","Non-Operational SQL","Nested Object Structured Language"],a:0,exp:"NoSQL stands for 'Not Only SQL' and refers to databases that provide flexible, non-relational data storage models."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"easy",q:"What is data redundancy?",opts:["Encrypting data twice","Storing the same data in multiple places unnecessarily","A database backup strategy","Indexing for faster queries"],a:1,exp:"Data redundancy occurs when the same data is stored in multiple places. Normalization aims to reduce it to maintain consistency."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"medium",q:"Which SQL retrieves all customers from Texas?",opts:["SELECT * FROM Customers IF state = 'TX';","SELECT * FROM Customers WHERE state = 'TX';","GET * FROM Customers WHERE state = 'TX';","SELECT Customers WHERE state = 'TX';"],a:1,exp:"The correct syntax is SELECT * FROM [table] WHERE [condition]. IF is not a valid SQL filtering keyword."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"medium",q:"Which SQL counts orders per customer?",opts:["SELECT customer_id, COUNT(*) FROM Orders;","SELECT customer_id, COUNT(*) FROM Orders GROUP BY customer_id;","SELECT COUNT(*) FROM Orders WHERE customer_id;","SELECT customer_id, TOTAL(*) FROM Orders GROUP BY customer_id;"],a:1,exp:"GROUP BY groups rows by customer_id, and COUNT(*) counts each group. Without GROUP BY, COUNT(*) returns one total number."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"medium",q:"Which SQL retrieves product names priced over 50, sorted highest to lowest?",opts:["SELECT name FROM Products WHERE price > 50 ORDER BY price ASC;","SELECT name FROM Products WHERE price > 50 SORT BY price DESC;","SELECT name FROM Products WHERE price > 50 ORDER BY price DESC;","SELECT name FROM Products HAVING price > 50 ORDER BY price DESC;"],a:2,exp:"ORDER BY price DESC sorts highest to lowest. SORT BY is not valid SQL, and HAVING is used after GROUP BY."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"medium",q:"OLAP is primarily used for:",opts:["Processing individual transactions quickly","Analyzing large datasets for business intelligence","Storing unstructured data","Encrypting database records"],a:1,exp:"OLAP (Online Analytical Processing) is optimized for complex analytical queries used in business intelligence and reporting."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"medium",q:"What is database normalization?",opts:["Encrypting sensitive data","Organizing a database to reduce redundancy and improve integrity","Copying data to a backup server","Indexing tables for faster queries"],a:1,exp:"Normalization is the process of structuring a relational database to eliminate redundancy and ensure data dependencies are logical."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"medium",q:"Social media posts and audio recordings are examples of:",opts:["Structured data","Semi-structured data","Unstructured data","Relational data"],a:2,exp:"Unstructured data has no predefined format or schema. Text, images, audio, and video all fall into this category."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"hard",q:"Which SQL correctly updates all product prices by 10%?",opts:["UPDATE Products price = price * 1.1;","UPDATE Products SET price = price * 1.1;","ALTER Products SET price = price * 1.10;","MODIFY Products SET price * 1.1;"],a:1,exp:"UPDATE [table] SET [column] = [expression] is the correct syntax. ALTER is for changing table structure, not data."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"hard",q:"Which SQL finds departments with average salary over 70000?",opts:["SELECT dept, AVG(salary) FROM Employees WHERE AVG(salary) > 70000 GROUP BY dept;","SELECT dept, AVG(salary) FROM Employees GROUP BY dept HAVING AVG(salary) > 70000;","SELECT dept, AVG(salary) FROM Employees GROUP BY dept WHERE AVG(salary) > 70000;","SELECT dept, AVG(salary) FROM Employees HAVING AVG(salary) > 70000;"],a:1,exp:"HAVING filters after aggregation. You cannot use aggregate functions in a WHERE clause \'97 WHERE filters before grouping."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"hard",q:"ACID \'97 what does Atomicity mean?",opts:["All operations in a transaction succeed or all are rolled back","Each transaction is isolated from others","Data remains valid after a transaction","Committed data persists after system failure"],a:0,exp:"Atomicity means a transaction is all-or-nothing. If any part fails, the entire transaction is rolled back to maintain integrity."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"hard",q:"What is a data warehouse primarily used for?",opts:["Real-time transaction processing","Storing and analyzing large volumes of historical data for business intelligence","Backing up operational databases","Running application servers"],a:1,exp:"A data warehouse stores historical, integrated data from multiple sources, optimized for analysis and reporting \'97 not live transactions."\},\
  \{t:"Data",d:"hard",q:"The CAP theorem states a distributed database can guarantee at most:",opts:["Consistency, Availability, and Partition Tolerance simultaneously","Two of: Consistency, Availability, Partition Tolerance","Speed, Accuracy, and Redundancy simultaneously","Encryption, Integrity, and Availability simultaneously"],a:1,exp:"The CAP theorem states a distributed system can only guarantee two of three: Consistency, Availability, and Partition Tolerance."\},\
  // Project Management\
